----------------------------------------------------------------
 PDF SECURITY — HOW IT WAS DONE
----------------------------------------------------------------

  PDFs (study notes and past papers) are displayed inside the
  platform but protected from easy downloading or printing.
  Here is exactly what was done and how each step works:


  STEP 1 — Display inside an iframe, not a direct link
  -------------------------------------------------------
  Instead of giving users a direct download link to the PDF
  file, the PDF is loaded inside an HTML <iframe> element
  embedded within the page. This means the user sees the
  content inside the platform rather than opening the file
  directly in a new tab or downloading it automatically.

  Example:
    <iframe id="pdfViewer" src="" width="100%" height="100%"
            style="display:none;"
            oncontextmenu="return false;">
    </iframe>


  STEP 2 — URL hash parameters to suppress browser PDF tools
  -----------------------------------------------------------
  When the PDF source is set, special hash parameters are
  appended to the file URL. These are browser-level hints
  that tell the built-in PDF viewer to hide its toolbar,
  navigation panel, and scrollbar controls:

    viewer.src = fileName + "#toolbar=0&navpanes=0&scrollbar=0";

    #toolbar=0   — hides the top toolbar (which contains the
                   download and print buttons in most browsers)
    #navpanes=0  — hides the side navigation/bookmarks panel
    #scrollbar=0 — hides the scrollbar UI in the PDF viewer

  This works in Chrome, Edge, and Firefox's built-in PDF
  viewers. It does not physically block downloading but
  removes the obvious one-click download button from view.


  STEP 3 — Right-click disabled on the iframe
  --------------------------------------------
  The oncontextmenu attribute is set to "return false" on
  every PDF iframe. This disables the right-click context
  menu on the viewer, preventing users from using the
  browser's "Save as" or "Open in new tab" options that
  would normally appear on right-click.

    oncontextmenu="return false;"


  STEP 4 — No direct download links in the UI
  --------------------------------------------
  In the Study Notes and Q&A Bank sections, buttons say
  "View" or "View Only" — not "Download". The JavaScript
  function that loads the PDF only sets the iframe src; it
  never creates an anchor tag with a download attribute or
  opens the file in a new window.


  WHERE THIS IS APPLIED
  ----------------------
  - questions.html     (Study Notes public page)
  - solutions.html     (Q&A Bank public page)
  - dashboard-student.html  (Study Notes and Q&A Bank
                             sections inside the dashboard)


  IMPORTANT LIMITATION
  ----------------------
  These measures make downloading inconvenient but do not
  make it technically impossible. A determined user could
  still:
    - Open browser developer tools and find the file URL
    - Type the direct file path into the address bar
    - Use browser extensions that bypass iframe restrictions

  True PDF protection would require serving PDFs through a
  PHP script that checks authentication before streaming the
  file, and storing PDFs outside the public web root folder.
  That level of protection was not implemented in this
  version but can be added as a future improvement.

